# Constant Function <GN>

The function <GN> is a constant function that always returns the value 5, regardless of the input integer provided. For any integer x, <GN>(x) = 5.

```
<GN>(3) = 5
<GN>(-7) = 5
<GN>(0) = 5
```

A key property of <GN> is that its derivative is always zero. This is characteristic of all constant functions, as they produce a horizontal line when graphed, with no change in output value regardless of changes to the input.

# The <JN> Function

The function <JN> is a constant function that always returns 7 regardless of the input value. For any integer x that is provided to <JN>, the output will always be 7.

```
<JN>(3) = 7
<JN>(42) = 7
<JN>(-10) = 7
```

A key property of <JN> is that it has a horizontal graph when plotted, forming a straight line at y = 7 across all x values. This means the derivative of <JN> is always zero, as there is no change in the output value regardless of changes to the input.

# Function <KN>: Constant Value Function

The function <KN> is a constant function that returns the value 9 for any integer input. No matter what integer is provided as input, <KN> will always output 9.

```
<KN>(0) = 9
<KN>(42) = 9
<KN>(-15) = 9
```

A key property of <KN> is that the derivative of this function is always zero. Since the output never changes regardless of the input value, there is no rate of change, making <KN> a horizontal line when graphed.

# Function <LN>: Constant Value Function

The function <LN> is a constant function that maps any integer input to the value 11. Regardless of what integer is provided as input, <LN> will always return 11.

```
<LN>(0) = 11
<LN>(42) = 11
<LN>(-7) = 11
```

A key property of <LN> is that it has a derivative of zero everywhere, making it horizontally flat when graphed. This makes <LN> useful in scenarios where a consistent, unchanging value is needed regardless of the input parameter.

# The Constant Function <MN>

The function <MN> is a constant function that always returns 13, regardless of the input value. For any integer x passed to <MN>, the output will always be 13.

```
<MN>(7) = 13
<MN>(-42) = 13
<MN>(0) = 13
```

A key property of <MN> is that it has a derivative of zero everywhere, making it the only function with this characteristic. This means the rate of change is always zero, as the function's output never varies regardless of changes to the input value.

# Constant Function <NN>

The function <NN> is a constant function that returns the value 15 for any integer input. Regardless of what integer value is passed to the function, the output will always be 15.

```
<NN>(0) = 15
<NN>(42) = 15
<NN>(-7) = 15
```

A key property of <NN> is that the difference between any two outputs is always zero, since all outputs are identical. This makes <NN> perfectly horizontal when graphed, appearing as a straight line parallel to the x-axis at y = 15.

# Function <PN>: Constant Function

The function <PN> is a constant function that returns the value 19 for any integer input. Regardless of what integer is passed to <PN>, it will always output 19.

```
<PN>(0) = 19
<PN>(42) = 19
<PN>(-7) = 19
```

A key property of <PN> is that it has zero slope, making it a horizontal line when graphed. This means the derivative of <PN> is always 0, as there is no change in the output value regardless of the input.

# Understanding the <QN> Function

The function <QN> is a constant function that maps any integer input to the value 21. Regardless of what integer you provide as input, the function will always return 21.

```python
# Examples of <QN> function
<QN>(0) # Returns 21
<QN>(42) # Returns 21
<QN>(-7) # Returns 21
```

A key property of <QN> is that it has a horizontal graph when plotted on a coordinate plane. Since the output is always 21 regardless of the input value, the graph forms a horizontal line at y = 21, making it easy to identify as a constant function.

# Function <RN>: Constant Output

The function <RN> is a constant function that maps any integer input to the constant value 23. Regardless of what integer value is provided as input, <RN> will always return 23.

```python
# Example usage of <RN>
<RN>(42)  # Returns 23
<RN>(-7)  # Returns 23
<RN>(0)   # Returns 23
```

A key property of <RN> is that it has a horizontal graph when plotted, appearing as a straight line at y = 23 across all x values. This makes <RN> particularly useful in scenarios where a consistent output value is required regardless of the input parameter.
